This paper is primarily focused on the dynamics of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs), which are commonly used in computer vision tasks such as image generation and classification. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), which is the primary subfield of GAN research. Additionally, the paper specifically mentions "vision tasks" and "mode collapse," which are common issues in computer vision, suggesting that cs.CV (Computer Vision) is also a likely category. The paper also discusses the theoretical analysis of GAN convergence behavior, which falls under the category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Furthermore, the paper mentions "vanishing gradients" and "oscillatory behavior," which are common issues in neural networks, suggesting that cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is also a possible category. Finally, the paper discusses the stability of GAN dynamics, which falls under the category of cs.SY (Systems and Control).
